85.initial_response: gridlock, or a situation in which the two branches of government are unable to pass legislation or make progress on important issues. This is because the two branches are controlled by different parties, and each party has different priorities and agendas. As a result, they are often unable to come to an agreement on important issues, leading to a stalemate.
